{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491287"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.12,0.13,0.55,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59536"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44944"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"94"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"6544"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42174"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of bilateral calf pain after walking 200 metres. Over this time the pain has been worse on walking uphill and relieved by rest. Over the last week, he has woken with pain in his feet and has had to dangle his legs over the edge of the bed for relief and the pain in his right foot has required tramadol for relief. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes (last HbA1c 9.4%) and untreated hypertension. His only regular medication is metformin. He is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears overweight. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Both lower limbs are shiny with hair loss and are markedly cool to touch, especially around the feet. The dorsalis pedis pulses are absent bilaterally. Buerger\u0027s test is positive bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lifestyle modification","Graded exercise program","Anticoagulation therapy","Revascularisation","Spinal surgery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of critical limb ischaemia (CLI), which is an advanced stage of peripheral arterial disease characterised by rest pain, tissue loss, or gangrene. The progression from intermittent claudication to rest pain requiring opioid analgesia indicates severe disease requiring urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERevascularisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as this patient has CLI. He requires urgent vascular surgical referral for imaging studies to define the anatomical distribution of disease and plan appropriate revascularisation, which may include endovascular intervention or surgical bypass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modification\u003C/strong\u003E including smoking cessation, diabetes control, and blood pressure management are essential but insufficient alone given the severity of disease. These should be implemented alongside definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraded exercise programs\u003C/strong\u003E are first-line treatment for stable intermittent claudication but are inappropriate for CLI where urgent revascularisation is required to prevent limb loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticoagulation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for acute limb ischaemia from thrombosis or embolism but not for chronic atherosclerotic disease unless there are other indications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for neurogenic claudication from spinal stenosis, which typically improves with forward flexion and worsens with extension. This patient\u0027s symptoms and signs are clearly vascular in origin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rest pain in peripheral arterial disease indicates critical limb ischaemia requiring urgent vascular surgical review.","Critical limb ischaemia is characterised by rest pain, tissue loss, or gangrene.","Risk factors for peripheral arterial disease include smoking, diabetes, and hypertension."],"references":["Conte MS, Bradbury AW, Kolh P et al. Global Vascular Guidelines on the Management of Chronic Limb-threatening Ischaemia. Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg 2019; 58: S1-S109. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31159978/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44944"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44944"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"